					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I know it's just marketing, but digging through the information on wiki.neogeodev.org has left me confused.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=177525#p177525" class="postlink">Espozo</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">a non &quot;GIGA POWER&quot; Neo Geo game is at most 330 mega bits<br /></div>How exactly did they arrive at 330 megabit?<br /><br />( <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://wiki.neogeodev.org/index.php?title=NEO-273">https://wiki.neogeodev.org/index.php?title=NEO-273</a><!-- m --> )<br /><br />On the <a href="https://wiki.neogeodev.org/index.php?title=CHA_board" class="postlink">CHA</a> board, ignoring any on-cart bankswitching:<br />The original Neo Geo C ROM layout nominally supports 2 Mi x 32bit, for 64 Mibit of sprite data.<br />The revised memory layout one uses the entire <em>24-bit</em> P bus <em>(plus CA4)</em> to support <s>16</s> 32 Mi x 32bit, or <s>512</s> 1024 Mibit of sprite data.<br />128 KiB (1Mibit) are always used for the S ROM (fix layer).<br />Z80: one 64 Ki x 8 bit (512 Kibit; M ROM) for the sound driver<br /><br />On the <a href="https://wiki.neogeodev.org/index.php?title=PROG_board" class="postlink">PROG</a> board, again ignoring any on-cart bankswitching:<br />68k: 512 Ki x 16bit (8 Mibit; P ROM), plus a bonus nonadjacent 512 Ki x16bit that I guess they weren't counting?<br />YM2610: two 16 Mi x 8 bit (total 256 Mibit; V ROM)<br /><br />so ... 256 Mibit(V) + 64 Mibit(C) + 8 Mibit(P) + 1 Mibit(S) + ½ Mibit(M) = 329½ Mibit? Is that what they were thinking?</div>

					
							<br /><br />
